## How to Run Tests

### Quick Start
```powershell
# 1. Start PostgreSQL
docker run --name postgres-utb-minute -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=postgres -p 5432:5432 -d postgres:latest

# 2. Create test database
docker exec postgres-utb-minute psql -U postgres -c "CREATE DATABASE utb_minute_test;"

# 3. Run tests
dotnet test UTB.Minute.WebApi.Tests
```

### Via Visual Studio
1. Open Test Explorer (Test → Test Explorer)
2. Click "Run All Tests"

### Individual Tests
```powershell
# Specific test class
dotnet test --filter "ClassName=UTB.Minute.WebApi.Tests.MealEndpointsTests"

# Specific test method
dotnet test --filter "Name=CreateMeal_WithValidData_ShouldReturnCreated"
```

## Test Examples

### Example 1: Creating a Meal
```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task CreateMeal_WithValidData_ShouldReturnCreated()
{
    // Arrange
    var createMealDto = new
    {
        name = "Nový pokrm",
        description = "Popis pokrmu",
        price = 150.00m
    };
    var content = new StringContent(
        JsonSerializer.Serialize(createMealDto),
        Encoding.UTF8,
        "application/json");

    // Act
    var response = await _httpClient.PostAsync("/meals", content);

    // Assert
    response.StatusCode.Should().Be(HttpStatusCode.Created);
    response.Headers.Location.Should().NotBeNull();
}
```

### Example 2: Order State Transition Validation
```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task UpdateOrderState_InvalidTransition_ShouldReturnBadRequest()
{
    // First change to Cancelled
    var cancelStateDto = new { state = 2 }; // Cancelled
    var cancelContent = new StringContent(...);
    await _httpClient.PutAsync("/orders/1/state", cancelContent);

    // Try invalid transition: Cancelled → Ready
    var updateStateDto = new { state = 1 }; // Ready
    var content = new StringContent(...);

    // Act
    var response = await _httpClient.PutAsync("/orders/1/state", content);

    // Assert
    response.StatusCode.Should().Be(HttpStatusCode.BadRequest);
}
```

